                            <lb/>
                        
                        THE MACMILLAN COMPANY
                            <lb/>
                        PUBLISHERS
                            <lb/>
                        60 FIFTH AVENUE
                            <lb/>
                        NEW YORK
                            <lb/>
                        
                        C.H. SEAVER, EDUCATIONAL DEPT.
                            <lb/>
                        R.R. SMITH, COLLEGE DEPT.
                            <lb/>
                        H.S. LATHAM, EDITORIAL      TRA<unclear reason="missing" cert="high">DE</unclear>
                            <lb/>
                        GEORGE P. BRETT JR. SALES   DE<unclear reason="missing" cert="high">PT</unclear>
                            <lb/>
                        J.N. MYERS, MEDICAL DEPT.
                            <lb/>
                        L.H. SEAMAN, JUVENILE DEPT.
                            <lb/>
                        W.H. MURRAY, RELIGIOUS DEPT.
                    </hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 19, 1926.</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>You ask for frank advice, in your letter of May 15th, and I am going to give it. I think this letter of Macy's is a very clever approach in the hope that Morrow may sooner or later publish something for you, and I want you to regard Macmillan as your publisher, and not to pass us up for anything. I believe that you yourself feel the wisdom of this policy. We are decidedly interested in your future, as you must know, and should feel quite disturbed to have you bring out something elsewhere.</p>
                
                <p>As to the Indian book: I think it would be unwise, whol<unclear>ly</unclear> aside from the feeling which I have mentioned, to bring out another Indian volume under your authorship wihtin the next year or so. We have Indian Tales coming along, and to publish another book of prose about Indians would be to dissipate the public's interest, with the result that neither book would get its maximum sale.</p> 
                
                <p>If, as I expect, Indian Tales does well, we can very pro<unclear>p</unclear>erly follow a year or two later with another book, and I shall be glad to discuss such a possibility with you.</p>
                
                <p>I have hope that for the present you will feel like writing Mr. Macy that your engagements with us at present are such as to preve<unclear>nt</unclear> 
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.12.33-34_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">34</fw>
                    <fw><hi rend="caps">SHEET NUMBER <add><fw type="authorial">2</fw></add> THE MACMILLAN COMPANY</hi></fw>
                    
                    us considering his kind proposal, etc., etc. Won't you?</p>
                
                <p>I return Macy's letter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours very truly,</salute>
                
                    <signed>H.S. Latham
                    THE MACMILLAN COMPANY.</signed>
                
                    <note>HSL.K</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
